.TH MBRPATCH 8 "2026" "mbr88 v0.2" "System Administration"
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NAME
.\"
mbrpatch \- view, edit, and transfer the MBR of an IBM XT-class hard disk
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH SYNOPSIS
.\"
.B mbrpatch
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbrpatch \-p
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbrpatch \-u
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbrpatch \-n
.I mbr_file
.br
.B mbrpatch \-r
.I mbr_file
.I device
.br
.B mbrpatch \-w
.I mbr_file
.I device
.br
.B mbrpatch \-h
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH DESCRIPTION
.\"
.B mbrpatch
reads, displays, and interactively edits the 512-byte Master Boot Record
of an IBM XT-class hard disk image.
It understands the standard four-entry MBR partition table and
the extended boot menu label feature of the
.B MBR88 v0.2
boot record.
.PP
It can also read the MBR directly from a physical disk device or write
a prepared image back to disk, removing the need for out-of-band tools
such as
.BR dd (1)
on Linux or
.B DEBUG
on DOS.
.PP
The program operates in one of six modes selected by a flag on the
command line.
When no flag is given the program runs in read-only view mode.
Modes that write to an image file always ask for confirmation and write
a backup copy immediately beforehand.
Device writes
.RB ( \-w )
are permanent and have no automatic backup; use
.B \-r
to save a copy before proceeding.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH MODES
.\"
.TP
.B mbrpatch \fImbr_file\fR
.B "View mode (read-only)."
Reads the file, validates it as a 512-byte MBR with a correct
.B 55\ AA
boot signature, prints the partition table, and exits.
This mode never modifies the file.
.TP
.B mbrpatch \-p \fImbr_file\fR
.B "Patch mode."
Validates the file then enters an interactive command session.
Partition table entries can be edited, deleted, and redefined.
If the
.B MBR88
signature is present and the version is exactly
.BR v0.2 ,
boot menu label editing is also available.
.TP
.B mbrpatch \-u \fImbr_file\fR
.B "Upgrade mode."
Validates the file, replaces its boot code with the
.B MBR88 v0.2
boot record, and preserves the existing partition table entries.
The file must already exist; use
.B \-n
to create a new image from scratch.
.TP
.B mbrpatch \-n \fImbr_file\fR
.B "New mode."
Creates a blank
.B MBR88 v0.2
image and enters the interactive command session.
The target file must
.I not
already exist.
.TP
.B mbrpatch \-r \fImbr_file\fR \fIdevice\fR
.B "Read disk mode."
Reads the first 512-byte sector from
.I device
and saves it to
.IR mbr_file .
The partition table is displayed before saving.
The output file must not already exist (safety check).
.PP
.RS
On Linux and ELKS,
.I device
is a path such as
.BR /dev/sda ,
.BR /dev/hda ,
or
.BR /dev/cda .
Writing to sector 0 requires root permissions.
.PP
On FreeDOS (Open Watcom build),
.I device
is the BIOS hard disk drive number expressed as a hex string:
.B 80h
for the first hard disk,
.B 81h
for the second, and so on.
Drive letters are not used because they may be remapped by redirectors
such as EtherDFS.
.RE
.TP
.B mbrpatch \-w \fImbr_file\fR \fIdevice\fR
.B "Write disk mode."
Loads
.I mbr_file
and validates it, displays the partition table, asks for confirmation,
then writes the 512-byte image to the first sector of
.IR device .
Device syntax is the same as
.BR \-r .
On Linux and ELKS a
.BR sync (2)
call is issued after the write to flush the kernel buffer cache.
.PP
.RS
.B This operation is permanent and there is no automatic backup.
Always run
.B \-r
first to save a copy of the existing MBR before using
.BR \-w .
.RE
.TP
.B mbrpatch \-h
Print a usage summary and exit.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
.\"
After loading a file in patch, upgrade, or new mode, the program presents
a two-column partition table display and a command prompt.
All changes are held in memory until explicitly written with
.BR w .
.PP
.TS
l l .
\fBg\fR	Set drive geometry (heads per cylinder, sectors per track).
	Must be run before \fBn\fR.  IBM XT default: 16 heads, 17 sectors.
\fBn\fR	Define a new partition or redefine an existing one.
	Requires geometry to have been set with \fBg\fR first.
\fBd\fR	Delete a partition slot.  Zeros the 16-byte entry and its label.
\fBt\fR	Change the partition type byte of an existing entry.
\fBb\fR	Toggle the bootable flag (inactive / bootable).
	See NOTES for MBR88 behaviour regarding this flag.
\fBv\fR	Set the boot menu volume label for a partition (MBR88 v0.2 only).
	Up to 11 characters, displayed in the boot menu.
\fBp\fR	Print the current state of the partition table.
\fBl\fR	List common partition type codes.
\fBw\fR	Ask for confirmation, write a backup to \fImbr_file\fB.bak\fR,
	then write the file.
\fBh\fR	Print the command summary.
\fBq\fR	Quit.  Prompts if there are unsaved changes.
.TE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH PARTITION TABLE FORMAT
.\"
The MBR partition table occupies 64 bytes at offset
.B 0x1BE
and holds four 16-byte entries in the IBM CHS format used by the original
PC/XT BIOS.
Each entry contains:
.PP
.TS
l l .
Byte 0	Status: 0x00 = inactive, 0x80 = bootable
Bytes 1\-3	CHS address of the first sector (packed)
Byte 4	Partition type (e.g. 01=FAT12, 06=FAT16B, 83=Linux)
Bytes 5\-7	CHS address of the last sector (packed)
Bytes 8\-11	LBA start sector (32-bit little-endian, computed from CHS)
Bytes 12\-15	LBA sector count (32-bit little-endian, computed from CHS)
.TE
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH MBR88 FEATURES
.\"
.B MBR88
is a custom MBR boot record for IBM XT-class hardware that presents an
interactive boot menu and always waits for the user to choose what to boot.
It supports hard disk partitions 1 through 4 and floppy drives A and B.
.PP
Only partitions with status byte
.B 0x80
appear in the
.B mbr88
boot menu.
Unlike conventional single-boot MBR loaders,
.B mbr88
permits more than one partition to be marked bootable
simultaneously; all marked partitions will appear in the menu.
Use the
.B b
interactive command to set the flag on each partition to be shown.
.PP
Conventional partitioning tools such as
.BR FDISK
enforce a single active partition.
After running such tools it is necessary to re-run
.B mbrpatch \-p
to restore the bootable flag on any additional boot partitions.
.PP
The
.B mbr88
boot record is identified by the five-byte ASCII signature
.B mbr88
at MBR offset
.BR 0x1B8 ,
followed by a version byte at
.BR 0x1BD .
Version
.B 0x01
corresponds to
.BR v0.2 .
.PP
When an
.B mbr88 v0.2
image is loaded, four 16-byte label slots at offset
.B 0x41
become editable via the
.B v
command.
Each slot holds up to 11 characters of ASCII text displayed in the boot menu.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH EXAMPLES
.\"
.B Save a backup of the live MBR before making any changes (Linux / ELKS):
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbrpatch \-r original.bin /dev/hda
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Save a backup of the live MBR before making any changes (FreeDOS):
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbrpatch \-r original.bin 80h
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B View the saved image without modifying it:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbrpatch original.bin
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Upgrade an existing MBR to mbr88, set labels, and write to the image file:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbrpatch \-u original.bin
.fi
.RE
At the prompt, use
.B g
to set geometry,
.B b
to mark bootable partitions,
.B v
to add labels, then
.B w
to write.
.PP
.B Write the finished image to disk (permanent, no undo):
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbrpatch \-w original.bin /dev/hda     (Linux / ELKS)
mbrpatch \-w original.bin 80h          (FreeDOS)
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Creating a new mbr88 image from scratch:
.PP
.RS
.nf
mbrpatch \-n new.bin
.fi
.RE
Use
.B g
then
.B n
to define partitions,
.B b
to mark them bootable,
.B v
to set labels, then
.B w
to write the file.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH NOTES
.\"
.B Bootable flag.
The status byte at offset 0 of each partition entry controls which
partitions
.B mbr88
shows in the boot menu.
Only bootable partitions are displayed.
Multiple partitions may safely be marked bootable simultaneously when
using
.B mbr88
as the boot loader.
Other MBR loaders typically require exactly one active partition.
.PP
.B Device writes.
The
.B \-w
mode writes directly to hardware and cannot be undone.
Always save a backup with
.B \-r
before using
.BR \-w .
On Linux and ELKS, writing sector 0 of a block device requires
root (superuser) permissions.
A
.BR sync (2)
call is issued automatically after the write on Linux and ELKS.
.PP
.B BIOS drive numbers.
On FreeDOS the disk is identified by its BIOS drive number.
.B 0x80
(written as
.B 80h
on the command line) is always the first hard disk.
.B 0x81
is the second.
Drive letters are deliberately not used because they may be remapped
by network redirectors and other drivers.
.PP
.B Backup files.
A backup of the image file is written to
.I mbr_file\fB.bak\fR
immediately before any write operation to that file.
No automatic backup is made when writing to a device with
.BR \-w .
.PP
.B Drive geometry.
IBM XT hard disks typically use 16 heads per cylinder and 17 sectors
per track.
Incorrect geometry produces wrong LBA start and size values.
XT-class BIOSes use only the CHS fields and ignore LBA, so this
rarely causes a problem in practice.
.\"
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.SH FILES
.\"
.TP
.I mbr_file.bak
Backup of the image file, written immediately before any write
to the file.
.TP
.I /usr/share/man/man8/mbrpatch.8
This manual page.
.\"
